Two weeks ago, the NSI published detailed data on mortality in Bulgaria in 2020, on the basis of which we made an interactive map by municipalities. The data are for the whole year and therefore lead to some decrease in the estimate of excess mortality, which is a direct result of the pandemic. If the country's excess for the March-December pandemic period is 19.5% compared to the average for the same period in 2015-2019, then the excess for the whole year is 14.6%. This is mainly due to the absence of a serious flu wave in the early 2020s. We have also added a map by municipalities showing the percentage of people who died from COVID compared to those diagnosed with COVID. This is the so-called Case Fatality Ratio (CFR). This information covers the period from the beginning of the pandemic to 22.01.2021. and is available from 265obshtini.bg who received it after an application to the Ministry of Home. As we have already noted in our work "Demographic and geographical impact of the COVID pandemic in Bulgaria and Eastern Europe in 2020", contrary to the widespread opinion in bulgaria, the big blow of the pandemic is not in the big cities, but is in the smaller peripheral areas of the country, where there is an acute shortage of medical and test resources. Such monitoring shall be confirmed by this information. It turns out that most of the most affected municipalities (marked in dark red) are not the municipalities district centers where the district medical resource is concentrated. Here are a few examples. For Vidin district, the municipality of Kula is most affected, for Silistra region these are the municipalities of Dulovo and Kaynardzha. In the last for 5000 people there is only one doctor and there is no pharmacy, and the regional town of Silistra is 30-35 km away - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S3qylW-qnFs. In Razgrad region, it is the municipality of Isperih. In Gabrovo region, dryanovo and Tryavna are the most affected. In sliven region this is the municipality of Kotel. In Pazardzhik district are the municipalities of Sarnitsa and Peshtera, and in plovdiv region this is the Municipality of Kuklen, which turns out to be the most affected throughout the country. In the most affected region of Smolyan the most affected are the municipalities of Dospat, Borino and Rudozem. The CFR map shows again that the highest values are in small municipalities. In Smolyansko in the municipalities of Edelino, Chepelare, Borino and Baths CFR is in the order of 16%-18%. This same municipality of Kaynardzha, in which there is no pharmacy, holds one of the records for the country for CFR of 23.7%. By comparison in Sofia, the CFR is 1.9.These CFR cosmic values can be interpreted in one way. Those tested in these municipalities are people who had a very severe clinical picture and who were tested when they were hospitalized (most likely and most often in the respective district town). these proceedings were not affected by the restrictive measures at any time. One of the leading hypotheses as to why in the Czech Republic they have been unable to control the situation for a long time, despite the imposition of far more serious measures than ours, is precisely the spread of infection among production groups, in which large groups of people work for a long time close to each other. This type of employment is not typical for Sofia, but this does not mean that it does not exist elsewhere in the country. For example, in full force it is valid for a number of Latin American countries. It is high time to start talking about this, because it can easily turn out that by the end of the summer there will be almost no vaccinated people in these municipalities. Exceeded Mortality by Municipalities - Bulgaria (2020)https://www.facebook.com/antoni.rangachev/posts/10159381614013011

By comparison in Sofia, the CFR is 1.9.These CFR cosmic values can be interpreted in one way. Those tested in these municipalities are people who had a very severe clinical picture and who were tested when they were hospitalized (most likely and most often in the respective district town). these proceedings were not affected by the restrictive measures at any time. One of the leading hypotheses as to why in the Czech Republic they have been unable to control the situation for a long time, despite the imposition of far more serious measures than ours, is precisely the spread of infection among production groups, in which large groups of people work for a long time close to each other. This type of employment is not typical for Sofia, but this does not mean that it does not exist elsewhere in the country. For example, in full force it is valid for a number of Latin American countries. It is high time to start talking about this, because it can easily turn out that by the end of the summer there will be almost no vaccinated people in these municipalities. Hidden text: Quote of: LillyM in pn, 26 Apr 2021, 21:06 Two weeks ago the NSI published detailed data on mortality in Bulgaria in 2020, on the basis of which we made an interactive map by municipalities. The data are for the whole year and therefore lead to some decrease in the estimate of excess mortality, which is a direct result of the pandemic. If the country's excess for the March-December pandemic period is 19.5% compared to the average for the same period in 2015-2019, then the excess for the whole year is 14.6%. This is mainly due to the absence of a serious flu wave in the early 2020s. We have also added a map by municipalities showing the percentage of people who died from COVID compared to those diagnosed with COVID. This is the so-called Case Fatality Ratio (CFR). This information covers the period from the beginning of the pandemic to 22.01.2021. and is available from 265obshtini.bg who received it after an application to the Ministry of Home. As we have already noted in our work "Demographic and geographical impact of the COVID pandemic in Bulgaria and Eastern Europe in 2020", contrary to the widespread opinion in bulgaria, the big blow of the pandemic is not in the big cities, but is in the smaller peripheral areas of the country, where there is an acute shortage of medical and test resources. Such monitoring shall be confirmed by this information. It turns out that most of the most affected municipalities (marked in dark red) are not the municipalities district centers where the district medical resource is concentrated. Here are a few examples. For Vidin district, the municipality of Kula is most affected, for Silistra region these are the municipalities of Dulovo and Kaynardzha. In the last for 5000 people there is only one doctor and there is no pharmacy, and the regional town of Silistra is 30-35 km away - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S3qylW-qnFs.
